TY  - JOUR
AU  - Christoffersen, Susan E. K.
AU  - Simutin, Mikhail
T1  - On the Demand for High-Beta Stocks: Evidence from Mutual Funds
PY  - 2017
Y1  - 2017/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhx022
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 30
IS  - 8
SP  - 2596
EP  - 2620
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Prior studies have documented that pension plan sponsors often monitor a fund’s performance relative to a benchmark. We use a first-difference approach to show that in an effort to beat benchmarks, fund managers controlling large pension assets tend to increase their exposure to high-beta stocks, while aiming to maintain tracking errors around the benchmark. The findings support theoretical conjectures that benchmarking can lead managers to tilt their portfolio toward high-beta stocks and away from low-beta stocks, which can reinforce observed pricing anomalies.Received March 20, 2014; editorial decision October 25, 2016 by Editor Laura Starks.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhx022
ER  - 



