TY  - JOUR
AU  - Chen, Andrew Y.
T1  - External Habit in a Production Economy: A Model of Asset Prices and Consumption Volatility Risk
PY  - 2017
Y1  - 2017/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhx047
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 30
IS  - 8
SP  - 2890
EP  - 2932
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - A standard real business-cycle model with external habit and capital adjustment costs matches a long list of asset price and business-cycle moments: equity, firm value, and risk-free rate volatility; the equity premium; excess return predictability; consumption growth predictability; basic moments of consumption, output, and investment; among others. The model also generates endogenous consumption volatility risk. Precautionary savings motives make consumption sensitive to shocks in bad times, leading to countercyclical volatility, even with homoscedastic technology shocks. Habit acts as countercyclical leverage, which amplifies this channel. Habit also implies high risk aversion, which amplifies the stock price response.Received April 21, 2016; editorial decision February 3, 2017 by Editor Stijn Van Nieuwerburgh.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhx047
ER  - 



